{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.72,0.05,0.1,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60241"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7106"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45661"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"7179"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60241"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe autonomic nervous system plays a crucial role in regulating heart rate. Various factors can influence heart rate, either increasing or decreasing it.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following results in a decreased heart rate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Noradrenaline release","Acetylcholine release","Endorphin release","Increased afterload","Dopamine release"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetylcholine release\u003C/strong\u003E results in a decreased heart rate. Acetylcholine is the primary neurotransmitter of the parasympathetic nervous system, which has an inhibitory effect on heart rate. The vagus nerve releases acetylcholine at the sinoatrial node, slowing the heart rate. This effect is known as the negative chronotropic effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline release\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with sympathetic nervous system activation, which typically increases heart rate. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased afterload\u003C/strong\u003E generally results in a reflex increase in heart rate to overcome the increased resistance to maintain cardiac output. \u003Cstrong\u003EEndorphin release\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edopamine release\u003C/strong\u003E do not directly decrease heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acetylcholine release by the parasympathetic nervous system decreases heart rate.","Noradrenaline, increased stroke volume, and increased afterload typically increase heart rate."],"references":["Gordan R, Gwathmey JK, Xie LH. Autonomic and endocrine control of cardiovascular function. World J Cardiol. 2015 Apr 26;7(4):204-14. doi: 10.4330/wjc.v7.i4.204. PMID: 25914789; PMCID: PMC4404375.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45661"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","i